title: I am part of this prestigious fellowship because… - Aaron's Story
details: The Knowledge House is proud of our efforts in Atlanta, Newark, and Los Angeles, where we launched our inaugural cohorts this fall. Many of the population, like Aaron Kaah, are bright and have full potential but lack the resources, opportunities, and exposure to gain entry into the growing tech sector. Over 50% of students who were admitted to our Fellowship programs did not have a laptop or wifi access to engage in our programming. What’s more, our students are in need of wraparound support, including mental health services, transportation, housing, and financial literacy, to help them persist and successfully graduate. How you can help: With our current match opportunity of $250,000 from a generous donor, you can help secure half a million in funding to support our Fellows throughout their journey in 2023! Your investment gives a Fellow access to instruction, career coaching, certifications, and the wraparound support they need to be successful. Support future technologists today! https://bit.ly/2022TKHFCDonate Check us out on our socials: Ig: @theknowledgehouse Facebook: @theknowledgehouse Twitter: @TheKnowledgeHou LinkedIn: The Knowledge House
text:
The Knowledge House is proud of our efforts in Atlanta, Newark, and Los Angeles, where we launched our inaugural cohorts this fall.  Many of the population, like Aaron Kaah, are bright and have full potential but lack the resources, opportunities, and exposure to gain entry into the growing tech sector. 

Over 50% of students who were admitted to our Fellowship programs did not have a laptop or wifi access to engage in our programming. What’s more, our students are in need of wraparound support, including mental health services, transportation, housing, and financial literacy, to help them persist and successfully graduate.  

How you can help:
  
With our current match opportunity of $250,000 from a generous donor, you can help secure half a million in funding to support our Fellows throughout their journey in 2023!  Your investment gives a Fellow access to instruction, career coaching, certifications, and the wraparound support they need to be successful.

title: I'm the first one in my family to graduate from college - Joselyn's Story
details: Joselyn Guaman immigrated to the US from Ecuador when she was just 11 years old. The first in her family to graduate from college, she came to the Knowledge House with a desire to pursue a career in Data Science. Together with the support of TKH staff, Joselyn successfully graduated and is now a K-12 coding instructor at Whizera. title: Black Women Pathblazing in Innovation
details: Come and join the conversation as we explore the state of hiring and funding for Black women innovators and celebrate the unique and powerful contributions Black women are making in the innovation sector. Our culminating event, "Black Women Path-blazing in Innovation" Featuring Asahi Pompey, President of @goldmansachs Foundation; Gabrielle Wyatt, Founder at The Highland Project; Rachel Williams, Former DEI Leader at Yelp, eBay, Alphabet; and Melanie Akwule, Founder & CEO of MINWO Inc.

title: How are companies protecting black lives 16 months later?
details: Ee examine the impact and progress of corporate support for Black lives 16 months after our national reckoning on racial injustice in the second installment of our live conversation series, "How are Companies protecting Black Lives 16 months later?" title: Let Me Live: Demo Day Presentation
details: Let Me Live is an app built by Shafee Ahmed, Stephanie Peña, Jahaziel Israel, and Naeem Shafi as part of our 2020 Innovation Fellowship. The app allows tenants to report harassment and poor living conditions, as well as allowing users to read the reports of others—all anonymously. This presentation was part of The Knowledge House's 2021 Demo Day.

title: 2020 Fellowship Campaign Recap
details: Last year, in the wake of the murder of George Floyd and a global pandemic, we launched the Fellowship Campaign to keep our organization afloat and advance our mission. Thanks to our amazing sponsors, funders, and staff, we were able to support 100 Fellows with the tools they needed to persist through virtual learning. This year we will be doubling our goal to reach 200 aspiring technologists in the next twelve months! On this National Nonprofit Day, we celebrate the increased impact we've made this year because of our supporters and we hope that our TKH family is ready to help us level up in 2021 as we grow our program nationally. If you are interested in volunteering, sponsoring or donating to the TKH Fellowship Campaign 2021, visit: https://www.theknowledgehouse.org/get...
text:
Last year, in the wake of the murder of George Floyd and a global pandemic, we launched the Fellowship Campaign to keep our organization afloat and advance our mission. Thanks to our amazing sponsors, funders, and staff, we were able to support 100 Fellows with the tools they needed to persist through virtual learning.

This year we will be doubling our goal to reach 200 aspiring technologists in the next twelve months! On this National Nonprofit Day, we celebrate the increased impact we've made this year because of our supporters and we hope that our TKH family is ready to help us level up in 2021 as we grow our program nationally.

If you are interested in volunteering, sponsoring or donating to the TKH Fellowship Campaign 2021, visit: https://www.theknowledgehouse.org/get...

title: Meet the Fellows 2021
details: Join us in conversation with two of TKH's Fellows, Quiana Berry and Ayman Omer, as they speak about the impact of TKH with industry professionals, Opal Hoyt and Dela Quist. The event was moderated by our Volunteer of the Month, Matthew Newton. About the panelists: Dela Quist is founder and CIO of Alchemy Worx and Touchstone estimates he has already clocked up over 20,000 hours thinking about email. As an email marketer, Dela Quist is at the top of his field. But his professional attributes are by no means his only strengths; his personal ones are equally valuable. With everything that he does – from mentoring young marketers to sharing his expertise with seasoned professionals – his passion and love for seeing this industry grow and championing the people who make it up is evident. His personality – albeit, larger than life – only contributes to this, driving him to see the best in the projects he undertakes and the contributions he pushes into this field A popular international speaker on all matters email, his thought-provoking views and lively style regularly receive rave reviews. Says Loren Macdonald of EVAdoption “Dela always takes a contrarian view that gets the industry talking – and often gets the smartest email folks to rethink their views.” Dela served many years as a member of the UK DMA's Email Marketing Council, he also served on the executive management group of the IAB, and on the steering committee of Future of European Advertising Stakeholders (FAST). Opal Hoyt is a career technology producer who has been working in digital publishing, startups and advertising for the past 10 years. After graduating from Columbia University with a degree in Art History, she found that digital publishing was an apt cross between her art and technology interests. She began her career working as a strategic consultant for a startup incubator and since then has worked as a technical producer and project manager at places like Conde Nast, Spotify, The New York Times, Publicis, McCann and more. She has spent much of this time freelancing and has most recently landed at Medecins Sans Frontieres (Doctors Without Borders) as a portfolio manager for technology & digital collaboration on their Systems team. In addition to work, Opal also spends free time working on her house in the West Catskills and writing/playing music with her band ZENIZEN. Matthew Newton is an Engineering Manager at Bloomberg, LP. Prior to that he worked at the IBM TJ Watson Research Center in Yorktown Heights, NY, where he was part of the team that developed the Blue Gene line of supercomputers. He has lived in Vietnam, Brazil, and Argentina, as well as four of the five boroughs. He has been a volunteer at The Knowledge House since 2018, a Board Member since 2019, and serves on the Development and Impact Committees. When not working or traveling internationally, he's usually occupied with entertaining his two young children, Elizabeth and Lucius.

title: Closing the Digital Divide: Los Angeles
details: Community and industry leaders are in conversation with The Knowledge House's CEO, Jerelyn Rodriguez, about how to close the digital divide in Los Angeles. About the panelists: Montea Robinson hails from New York City, having recently relocated to California as Managing Director of Ghetto Film School Los Angeles. After completing a BFA in Experimental Film from the SUNY Purchase School of Film and Media studies, Montea began her career as a broadcast and post production producer in commercial advertising. Dedicated to serving young people with a passion for the arts, she is thrilled to continue this work in Los Angeles through Ghetto Film School. Tyler Bell is the Managing Partner of EleventoOne, a creative social-impact consulting firm that provides entrepreneurs and organizations with the tools, resources and strategies needed to bring their vision to life. With over 10 years of experience living and serving at the intersection of People Operations, Education, Policy, and Technology, Tyler uniquely understands how to build community while creating sustainable change. He is an advocate, advisor, and active volunteer for several local & global social impact organizations. Additionally, Tyler enjoys spending time with loved ones, practicing mindfulness, traveling, sports, and finding the best food in every neighborhood. Sergio Rosas Sergio is the CEO and Founder of Next Shift Learning, a workforce design studio that builds economic freedom by shifting mindsets to shift futures ultimately. He has over a decade of experience designing, building, and launching local and national programs that aim to make the technology industry equitable through learning and capacity investments in communities of color through partnerships with employers and public institutions. His work has gained visibility in Los Angeles as the founding Director of the LA Tech Talent Pipeline, a partnership with Mayor Eric Garcetti and the Los Angeles Area of Chamber. This Pipeline placed 500 low-income youth and young adults in tech internships and provided 15,000 students with work-based learning experiences. Sergio earned his Master’s in Learning, Design, and Technology and his Bachelor’s (honors) in Political Science and Comparative Studies in Race and Ethnicity from Stanford University. Kari Weber is the Branch Manager at Dress for Success Worldwide West, the only free global employment resource for women. In this role Kari is responsible for all operations and program management; working to serve as many women as possible and help get them on the path to economic independence. Kari brings a wealth of experience in workplace operations, relationship building and events to this job and is thrilled to use her skills in such an impactful way.

title: Closing the Digital Divide: Newark
details: Community and industry leaders are in conversation with The Knowledge House's CEO, Jerelyn Rodriguez, about how to close the digital divide in Newark. About the panelists: A’Dorian Murray-Thomas is the Founder and CEO of SHE Wins Inc., a leadership and mentoring organization for girls in Newark. A’Dorian founded SHE Wins to create a pipeline of college, career, and community-ready young women leaders, working particularly with young women who share her story of losing a loved one to gun violence. A’Dorian previously served at the Newark Opportunity Youth Network where she helped tackle Newark’s dropout and suspension crisis through innovative alternative education and restorative justice programs. A’Dorian recently made history where at 23 years old, she became the youngest woman ever elected to the Newark Board of Education, the largest school district in the state of New Jersey. A’Dorian has been recognized as a President Obama White House Champion of Change, Glamour Magazine “College Woman of the Year”, Youth Service America “Everyday Young Hero”, “The Root” Magazine Young Futurist, and has been a recipient of over a dozen additional awards for her work in education and youth development. A fierce advocate for gender, racial, and educational equity, A’Dorian is currently an NAACP NextGen Leadership Fellow, School Board Partners Education Policy Fellow, and a recent graduate of the Higher Heights National Black Women Leaders Fellowship. A’Dorian is a 2016 graduate of Swarthmore College and holds a B.A. in Political Science and Educational Studies. Generra Rodriguez is the Recruitment and Community Engagement Coordinator for The Knowledge House and a Newark native. She has gone from being a student at University High School and Rutgers Newark to then building a career in education and tech. Her passion for education has led her down a path of student recruitment and community outreach for Newark Board of Education and now The Knowledge House. She hopes to help her community continue learning and growing so that everyone can reach their full potential. Calvin Ledford is President of the PSEG Foundation and Director of PSEG Corporate Social Responsibility. In this role, Mr. Ledford has oversight of the philanthropic areas of corporate citizenship: volunteerism, corporate giving and the Foundation’s programs operations. In June 2020, PSEG and the PSEG Foundation announced the launch of the new Powering Equity and Social Justice Initiative, which includes a $1 million commitment to support organizations that address equity, racial injustice and human rights in communities of color. Prior to this role, Calvin’s over 30-year career at PSEG has allowed him to work extensively with communities and stakeholders all across our service territory. Mr. Ledford is very active in the community. Mr. Ledford is a graduate of Hampton University. He is also a distinguished alumni of Leadership Newark and Lead New Jersey. Dominique D. Lee is the founder and Chief Executive Officer of Building Resilient Intelligent Creative Kids (BRICK) Education Network. BRICK is an education management nonprofit based in Newark, New Jersey, that serves children and families together through a two-generation approach. Its mission is to relentlessly knock down all barriers to students’ academic success so that each and every child has an unimpeded path to unlocking their limitless potential. Dominique has been awarded the Leaders and Legends Award for Outstanding Achievement in Early Childhood Education by Programs for Parents, the Russ Berrie Making a Difference award by The Russell Berrie Foundation, and the Young Changemakers Award by the Community Foundation of New Jersey. Dominique received his B.A. in political science from the University of Michigan and his M.A. in education leadership from New York University.

title: Closing the Digital Divide: Atlanta
details: Community and industry leaders are in conversation with The Knowledge House's CEO, Jerelyn Rodriguez, about how to close the digital divide in Atlanta. About the panelists: Candice L Dixon is the Coalition Development Director for NPower. Candice is a non-profit leader with more than 15 years of experience supporting local (Atlanta), national and international organizations. Her work has centered on community building, health equity, human trafficking, gender equity, and programming empowering women and girls. She is a committed community leader and a proud member of Delta Sigma Theta Sorority and the LEAD Atlanta Class of 2015. Ryan Shepard is the Executive Director of the CARE Atlanta Global Innovation Hub. He was born and raised in Los Angeles, California and is a graduate of Morehouse College and the Harvard Graduate School of Education. Ryan was a 2011 Catherine B. Reynolds Foundation Fellow in Social Entrepreneurship at the Harvard Kennedy School Center for Public Leadership. Before joining CARE in late 2018, Ryan spent time professionally at McKinsey & Co., the City of Atlanta and Purpose Built Schools Atlanta. Darrell Booker leads one of Microsoft’s most important racial equity commitments, the Nonprofit Tech Acceleration of Black and African American Communities, a national program designed at leveling the tech playing field for nonprofits serving our most underserved communities. Darrell also co-founded a tech startup for the fitness industry used in hundreds of gyms across the U.S. and Canada. Prior to leading this program, Darrell served in an advisor role helping the world’s largest nonprofits on their digital transformation to the cloud.

details: A fireside chat between powerhouse Black leaders in sports and philanthropy who have all leveraged their career success to make a positive impact on racial justice. Takeaways for attendees will include ideas from innovators about kickstarting their personal social impact and philanthropy practice.

title: UNPACKING: Hiring Bias in Technology - Gender Bias and Credentialing in Technology
details: The second and final part of our "Unpacking Hiring Bias in Technology" series entitled "Gender Bias and Credentialing in Technology" focuses on gender bias, credentialing, and how the lack of representation in employee hiring decisions perpetuates an environment dominated by men. Jessica Santana, Co-founder & CEO at America On Tech, Jalisa Watson, Creative Project Manager at Snap Inc., and Obioma Richardson, Global Finance-SAP Project Analyst at Bloomberg and founder of Watch her Win, joins The Knowledge House's Director of Strategic Partnerships, Constance Barnes, in the conversation.

title: UNPACKING: Hiring Bias in Technology - Racial Bias and Credentialing in Technology
details: The first part from our "Unpacking Hiring Bias in Technology" series entitled "Racial Bias and Credentialing in Technology" focuses on roadblocks Black professionals face during the hiring process. Courtney Blount, Business Marketing Manager at Snap Inc., Rah Thomas, Cloud First Infrastructure Account Lead at Accenture, and Jesse Owens II, VP of Product, Open Banking at Wells Fargo, joins The Knowledge House's Associate Director of Development, Derrick Spencer, in conversation with industry professionals
